Reason through the epistemological problem of using Playwright-based synthetic testing for web quality assurance. Playwright runs a real Chromium browser and can execute JavaScript, interact with the DOM, and measure performance metrics. But it is a single browser engine running on server infrastructure under laboratory conditions. What is the relationship between what Playwright measures and the actual user experience?

Consider the layers of abstraction and their associated measurement errors: Playwright's Chromium instance runs on Linux server hardware with no GPU acceleration for rendering (or minimal GPU support depending on configuration) — how does this affect performance metrics that involve rendering and compositing? Playwright runs in a headless or headed mode without a real display — does this affect layout calculations? The server running Playwright has different CPU performance characteristics than a user's device — how does this affect JavaScript execution timing?

For accessibility testing specifically: Playwright accesses the DOM and the accessibility tree. The accessibility tree is what screen readers consume. But Playwright's accessibility tree snapshot may differ from what a real screen reader (NVDA on Windows, VoiceOver on macOS, TalkBack on Android) actually announces, because screen readers apply their own interpretation layer on top of the accessibility tree. What are the known gaps between accessibility tree analysis and real screen reader behavior?

For visual regression testing: Playwright captures screenshots at a specified viewport size. Real users have different zoom levels, font size preferences (system default font size, browser zoom), high-DPI displays (devicePixelRatio 2 or 3), and OS-level display settings (high contrast mode, color blindness filters). To what extent do Playwright screenshots represent the visual experience of real users?

Reason through what the correct epistemic status of synthetic test results is: are they ground truth, strong evidence, weak evidence, or primarily useful for detecting regressions relative to a baseline? What should be communicated to users of an automated web quality tool about the limitations of its findings?
